After reading all the great reviews, I had high expectations for this dish. Everyone else seemed to like it as an alternative to the same old turkey sandwich stuff, but I wasn't particularly impressed. I would give it two forks myself (like it, don't love it), but the three other people who ate it thought it was really good, so I'm bumping it up to three forks.

Rating: 4
So easy--and so, so good. I made this with leftover Thanksgiving turkey, taking the previous reviewer's suggestions to add black beans and sweet potato and sub garam masala for pumpkin spice (which I didn't have). I did find that, with the added ingredients, I needed to add an extra half-cup of chicken broth. It was a hit!

Rating: 3
I made this for an office Christmas lunch.I put in black beans and sweet potato chunks in addition to the listed ingredients. It was well received. I think this recipe could use Garam Masala spice blend in place of Pumpkin pie spice-my pumpkin pie spice blend had sugar in it, and that just seems strange in a supper dish. Also, I think orange wedges, dried apricots or other fruit could be put in the dish (late in cooking) to add an extra exotic feel. Also, the fruits' sweetness would counter hot pepper put in. *Garam Masala is Indian, it includes cinnamon,coriander,black pepper, cumin, cloves. And it smells fantastic.

